nited Kingdom":"Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ramsbury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a habitational name from a place so named near Gunzenhausen, Franconia. This surname is not found in Germany.","Alternatively, perhaps an altered form of German <b>Ramsberg</b> or <b>Ramsberger</b>: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany called Ramsberg. The surname <i>Ramsberg</i> is very rare in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Ransburg","meanings":["German: variant of   Ramsburg  . This surname is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Remsberg","meanings":["Altered form of German <b>Ramsberg</b> or <b>Ramsberger</b> (see   Ramsburg  ), or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Neil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the enduringly popular Gaelic name   Niall .  From the Middle Ages onwards, this name was found mainly in Ireland, the Highlands of Scotland, and the English-Scottish Border region. However, since the 20th century it has spread to enjoy considerable popularity in all parts of the English-speaking world, although in England it has recently been overtaken by the Gaelic form."],"variants":[{"name":"Neal","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Neil ."]},{"name":"Neale","meanings":["Anglicized form of the enduringly popular Gaelic name   Niall .  From the Middle Ages onwards, this name was found mainly in Ireland, the Highlands of Scotland, and the English-Scottish Border region. However, since the 20th century it has spread to enjoy considerable popularity in all parts of the English-speaking world, although in England it has recently been overtaken by the Gaelic form."]}]},{"name":"Nigel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval name <i>Nigellus</i>, a Latinized version (ostensibly representing a diminutive of Latin <i>niger</i> ‘black’) of the vernacular <i>Ni(h)el</i>, i.e.   Neil .  Although it is frequently found in medieval records, this form was probably not used in everyday life before its revival by antiquarians such as  Sir Walter  Scott in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Mistress of Neil Nigel Ramsbury was born about 1104, in Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Bishop Neal \"Nigel\" of Ely Le Poer. She died in Ely, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1104–":"umbes 1104–Surnud","1100–1169":"1100–1169","1120–1198":"1120–1198","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","1100":"1100","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","Abt 1104":"umbes 1104","Ely, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ely, Cambridgeshire, , England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ramsbury, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1104–":"noin 1104–Kuollut","1100–1169":"1100–1169","1120–1198":"1120–1198","1104–Female":"1104–Kuollut","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","1100":"1100","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","Abt 1104":"noin 1104","Ely, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ely, Cambridgeshire, , England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ramsbury, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1104–":"environ 1104–Décédée","1100–1169":"1100–1169","1120–1198":"1120–1198","1104–Female":"1104–Décédée","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","1100":"1100","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","Abt 1104":"environ 1104","Ely, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Ely, Cambridgeshire, , England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ramsbury, Wiltshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Maud Mistress of Neil Nigel Ramsbury est née environ 1104, à Ramsbury, Wiltshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Bishop Neal \"Nigel\" of Ely Le Poer. Elle est décédée à Ely, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"Abt 1104–":"um 1104–Verstorben","1100–1169":"1100–1169","1120–1198":"1120–1198","1104–Female":"1104–Verstorben","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","1100":"1100","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","Abt 1104":"um 1104","Ely, Cambridgeshire,